"# Chapter 12 — Apropos and search: introspecting by shape

You know what you want. You do not remember what the verb is called. Search bridges the gap.

Motoi's search family runs over the registry (Chapter 11) with different match criteria: by name (`apropos`), by arity, by contract shape, by doc-string content. Each is one filter over the registry. Each returns a list of verb names.

## 12.1 apropos — the workhorse

`apropos` takes a regex or substring and returns every verb whose name matches.

```scheme
(apropos \"sort\")
;; => (sort sort-by sort! sorted? unsort merge-sort)

(apropos \"cortex\")
;; => (cortex/read cortex/write cortex/record cortex/query cortex/remember cortex/recall)

(apropos \"paint-.*\")
;; => (paint-dot paint-line paint-circle paint-arc paint-rect ...)
```

At the REPL: `,apropos <regex>` prints the matching names one per line, sorted.

The default match is a regex if the string looks regex-y, substring otherwise. Motoi's implementation lives in `src/repl.js` line 69.

## 12.2 verbs-in-namespace

`(verbs-in-namespace ns)` returns every verb whose name is prefixed with `ns/`. This was shown in Chapter 11.

```scheme
(verbs-in-namespace \"composer\")
;; => (composer/canvas composer/slider composer/button ...)
```

Namespace scope for search when you know the family.

## 12.3 doc-search

Search doc strings (not just names) for a keyword:

```scheme
(define (doc-search keyword)
  (filter
    (lambda (n)
      (let ((d (doc-of n)))
        (and d (string-contains d keyword))))
    (map car (snapshot-registry))))

(doc-search \"predicate\")
;; => every verb whose doc mentions the word predicate
```

Doc-search finds verbs whose name does not include the concept but whose behavior does. Chapter 11's grep-docs was the same pattern.

