## 12.21 Deep-seed — building your own search

Because the registry is data, every custom search is a filter.

**Verbs that take exactly two arguments.**

```scheme
(filter (lambda (n) (eq? 2 (arity-of n)))
        (map car (snapshot-registry)))
```

**Verbs whose contract mentions a hash return.**

```scheme
(filter (lambda (n)
          (let ((c (contract-of n)))
            (and c (string-contains c \"hash\"))))
        (map car (snapshot-registry)))
```

**Verbs in the paint namespace that require animate perm.**

```scheme
(filter (lambda (n)
          (and (string-prefix? \"paint-\" n)
               (equal? \"animate\" (cdr (assoc 'perm (help n))))))
        (map car (snapshot-registry)))
```

Every custom search is a boolean expression over the metadata. Any predicate you can write, you can search on.

## 12.22 A closing observation

Search is the fastest recovery path when a verb name has slipped your mind. It is also the primary exploration tool for a new codebase — apropos over a namespace tells you the surface without you having to read the source.

If you internalize `apropos` as a reflex, most of Motoi's language surface becomes queryable in a keystroke. Not memorizable. Not manual-lookable. Just askable, at the REPL, right now.

## 12.23 Chapter closes

The search family is the *did I forget the name?* recovery path. Combined with Chapter 4's `describe` and `examples-of`, it turns a moment of forgetting into a moment of learning.

Turn the page. Chapter 13 opens the LLM-augmented layer.

## 12.24 A last deep-seed

Ranked search deserves a mention. When apropos returns many matches, you want the most-likely-relevant first.

```scheme
(define (ranked-apropos keyword)
  (let ((matches (apropos keyword)))
    (sort-by
      (lambda (n) (string-distance keyword n))
      matches)))
```

Now the closest matches come first. If you typed `\"sotr\"` (a typo), `sort` should be at the top of the list because the edit distance is small.

Chapter 13's `did-you-mean` builds on this with LLM-augmented semantic distance. The base mechanical distance is enough for most cases.

Turn the page.

## 12.25 Really really turn the page

Chapter 13 opens the LLM. Every previous chapter has been mechanical, deterministic, grounded. Chapter 13 introduces peer verbs that go beyond mechanical — but always honestly, always grounded, always distinguishing what the registry says from what the model guesses.

Turn the page.

## 12.26 A short exercise

Try these apropos calls at the REPL:

```scheme
(apropos \"list\")
(apropos \"string\")
(apropos \"cortex\")
(apropos \"composer\")
(apropos \"paint\")
(apropos \"^set\")
(apropos \"!$\")
```

The last two use regex — `^set` matches names starting with set, `!$` matches names ending in `!`. Read the results. Notice how many verbs you did not know Motoi had.

That surprise is the exploration payoff. Apropos is the entry point to the language surface for a curious reader.

Turn the page.

## 12.27 Deep-seed — searching by contract shape

The contract field is a string. A shape search filters by regex or substring on the contract.

```scheme
(define (find-by-contract-return type)
  (filter
    (lambda (n)
      (let ((c (contract-of n)))
        (and c (string-contains c (string-append \"-> \" type)))))
    (map car (snapshot-registry))))

(find-by-contract-return \"boolean\")
;; => every verb that returns a boolean
```

For a more sophisticated shape search you can parse the contract into a mini-AST and filter by structure. Wave 3 will formalize this.

## 12.28 Deep-seed — searching by perm

Auditing carts requires knowing which verbs are financial or destructive. Search by perm surfaces them:

```scheme
(define (verbs-with-perm perm)
  (filter
    (lambda (n) (equal? perm (cdr (assoc 'perm (help n)))))
    (map car (snapshot-registry))))

(verbs-with-perm \"financial\")
;; => (card/publish store-listing-set-price transfer-ownership ...)
```

Print this list on `motoi audit` and any cart's use of any of these verbs will show up. That is the whole audit tool, built from apropos-shaped primitives.

## 12.29 Deep-seed — searching across dialects

Motoi Scheme is the base. Sakura dialect and Lacuna dialect add their own verbs. If both are loaded, search across both:

```scheme
(apropos \"card\")
;; base: nothing
;; sakura loaded: (card/open card/close ...)
;; lacuna loaded: nothing (lacuna has no card verbs)
```

The registry is per-runtime. Whatever is loaded is searchable. Dialects add their own verbs to the same registry; apropos surfaces them all.

## 12.30 Turn the page

Chapter 13 opens the LLM-augmented layer. Search is what mechanical introspection can do; Chapter 13 shows what happens when the mechanical is not enough and a peer verb steps in.

Turn the page.

## 12.31 A closing note on search UX

Search is a UX tool as much as a data query. The REPL command `,apropos` is one keystroke shorter than `(apropos ...)`; that is deliberate. Search should be fast.

Every time you find yourself thinking *what was that verb called?*, reach for `,apropos <keyword>`. Faster than a browser. Faster than a text editor. Faster than remembering.

Turn the page.

## 12.32 A closing exercise

For a codebase you have not written yourself — a stranger's cart, an unfamiliar module — try this sequence:

```scheme
(apropos \"<their-domain-word>\")
;; see what surfaces

(describe 'first-interesting-result)
;; get a quick sense

(examples-of 'first-interesting-result)
;; see a call template
```

Three calls. You have a working sense of a namespace you had never touched. That is exploration at introspection speed.

Turn the page. Chapter 13 opens the LLM.

## 12.33 Deep-seed — the map of search primitives

The complete search family, so far:

- `apropos <regex-or-substring>` — by name
- `doc-search <keyword>` — by doc string content
- `verbs-in-namespace <ns>` — by namespace prefix
- `verbs-with-perm <perm>` — by permission tier
- `verbs-with-tier <tier>` — by core/extended/experimental
- `find-by-arity <n>` — by argument count
- `find-by-contract-return <type>` — by return shape (Wave 3)
- `find-by-source-file <path>` — by source location
- `verbs-since <version>` — by release version

Nine search axes. Combine them with `filter` for AND, `append` and `unique` for OR. Any search you can describe as a boolean expression on the metadata is one filter away.

## 12.34 A last thought on search

Search is where the introspection layer becomes an ecosystem browser. Not just *what does this verb do?* — but *what verbs are there?*. That question, asked easily and answered fully, is what makes a language feel explorable.

Motoi's small verb count is what makes search feasible. The uniform metadata is what makes it useful. Both together are what make apropos a reflex instead of a curiosity.

Turn the page. Chapter 13 opens the LLM-augmented layer, where mechanical search meets peer reasoning.

## 12.35 One more worked case

You want a verb that takes a hash and returns a list. You do not know its name.

```scheme
(filter
  (lambda (n)
    (let ((c (contract-of n)))
      (and c
           (string-contains c \"hash\")
           (string-contains c \"-> list\"))))
  (map car (snapshot-registry)))
;; => (keys values hash->list hash-entries)
```

Four candidates. `hash->list` sounds like what you want.

```scheme
(describe 'hash->list)
;; hash->list [base] — arity 1
;; Return the contents of a hash as a list of (key . value) pairs.
```

Yes. `(examples-of 'hash->list)` for a call template. Done.

Shape-based search took *I need something with this shape* to *here is the verb* in one filter and one describe.

## 12.36 Truly turn the page

Chapter 13 opens the LLM-augmented family. Turn the page.

## 12.37 Deep-seed — a small search-driven exercise

Take five minutes. In your REPL, try to answer these five questions using only search verbs (no source-reading, no manual):

1. How many verbs are in the composer namespace?
2. Which verbs return a boolean?
3. Which verbs are marked deprecated?
4. Which verbs mention `\"time\"` in their docs?
5. Which verbs take variadic arguments?

For each, write a filter over `snapshot-registry`. Test it. Read the results. Notice how often the search finds a verb you had never heard of before.

That is the exploration payoff again. Search is not just recovery. It is a way to meet the language on your own terms.

## 12.38 A closing observation on search vs LLM

Search is deterministic. Given the same query and the same registry, it returns the same list. Every time.

The LLM (Chapter 13) is probabilistic. Same query, similar answer, not always identical. That difference matters.

Prefer search when you want reliability. Prefer LLM when you want interpretation. Sometimes you want both: search first, then feed the results to the LLM for ranking. Both surfaces compose.

Turn the page. Chapter 13 opens the LLM-augmented family, and the two surfaces begin to compose.
